the right signatures.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring findClass and security manager issues**\\n\\nI'm examining the `findClass` method and how to implement a public wrapper like `findLoadedPublic` to call `findLoadedClass`. For `getPackage`, I see it can also be a public wrapper. So, I can instantiate a Direct subclass that utilizes these public wrapper methods. When calling `Direct.findClass`, the `Method.invoke` should bypass module issues. But wait, I have concerns around initializing if the current security manager triggers permission checks, especially given some restrictions in JDK 21. I need to check how I could potentially manipulate the System settings or install a SecurityManager. This could get tricky!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test environment and dynamic loading**\\n\\nI’m wondering if my test environment could allow for the changes I want since it seems prior tests didn’t instantiate Direct. I plan to install a public test outside the library package, potentially including `org_modelmapper.modelmapper`. For dynamic class loading, I might need to use a Native pattern and catch UnsupportedFeature errors. Using ByteBuddy to generate a class should work, but I should be careful when calling the `defineClass` wrapper. I may also have to handle UnsupportedOperationException if it arises. Access to the Direct type is crucial here!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering security manager in JDK21**\\n\\nI'm trying to clarify the coverage details about the security manager in JDK21. It seems that if the system isn’t set with the -Djava.security.manager=allow option, it throws an UnsupportedOperationException when attempting to set the security manager. I wonder if this behavior has been the default “disallow” since Java 18. It’s a bit confusing, and I’d like to be sure I understand the implications of these changes.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_fx0MWdfaCigD0ybNgv4nXkHa|fc_0f375a81f4ff