 right signatures.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring findClass and security manager issues**\\n\\nI'm examining the `findClass` method and how to implement a public wrapper like `findLoadedPublic` to call `findLoadedClass`. For `getPackage`, I see it can also be a public wrapper. So, I can instantiate a Direct subclass that utilizes these public wrapper methods. When calling `Direct.findClass`, the `Method.invoke` should bypass module issues. But wait, I have concerns around initializing if the current security manager triggers permission checks, especially given some restrictions in JDK 21. I need to check how I could potentially manipulate the System settings or install a SecurityManager. This could get tricky!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test environment and dynamic loading**\\n\\nI’m wondering if my test environment could allow for the changes I want since it seems prior tests didn’t instantiate Direct. I plan to install a public test outside the library package, potentially including `org_modelmapper.modelmapper`. For dynamic class loading, I might need to use a Native pattern and catch UnsupportedFeature errors. Using ByteBuddy to generate a class should work, but I should be careful when calling the `defineClass` wrapper. I may also have to handle UnsupportedOperationException if it arises. Access to the Direct type is crucial here!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering security manager in JDK21**\\n\\nI'm trying to clarify the coverage details about the security manager in JDK21. It seems that if the system isn’t set with the -Djava.security.manager=allow option, it throws an UnsupportedOperationException when attempting to set the security manager. I wonder if this behavior has been the default “disallow” since Java 18. It’s a bit confusing, and I’d like to be sure I understand the implications of these changes.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_fx0MWdfaCigD0ybNgv4nXkHa|fc_0f375a81f4ffd7800169fc109847008197b2a4ff27ce0f34a3", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "jshell <<'EOF'\ntry { System.setSecurityManager(new SecurityManager()); System.out.println(\"ok \" + System.getSecurityManager()); } catch (Throwable t) { t.printStackTrace(); }\nEOF", "timeout": 10}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1078, "output": 1620, "cacheRead": 27136, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 29834, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1778126976866, "responseId": "resp_0f375a81f4ffd7800169fc108155a48197ade4d6dd9b91c69a"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_fx0MWdfaCigD0ybNgv4nXkHa|fc_0f375a81f4ffd7800169fc109847008197b2a4ff27ce0f34a3", "toolName": "bash", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "|  Welcome to JShell -- Version 25.0.2\n|  For an introduction type: /help intro\n\njshell> java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException: Setting a Security Manager is not supported\n\tat java.base/java.lang.System.setSecurityManager(System.java:303)\n\tat REPL.$JShell$2.do_it$($JShell$2.java:5)\n\tat java.base/jdk.internal.reflect.DirectMethodHandleAccessor.invoke(DirectMethodHandleAccessor.java:104)\n\tat java.base/java.lang.reflect.Method.invoke(Method.java:565)\n\tat jdk.jshell/jdk.jshell.execution.DirectExecutionControl.invoke(DirectExecutionControl.java:227)\n\tat jdk.jshell/jdk.jshell.execution.RemoteExecutionControl.invoke(RemoteExecutionControl.java:121)\n\tat jdk.jshell/jdk.jshell.execution.DirectExecutionControl.invoke(DirectExecutionControl.java:125)\n\tat jdk.jshell/jdk.jshell.execution.ExecutionControlForwarder.processCommand(ExecutionControlForwarder.java:148)\n\tat jdk.jshell/jdk.jshell.execution.ExecutionControlForwarder.commandLoop(ExecutionControlForwarder.java:266)\n\tat jdk.jshell/jdk.jshell.execution.Util.forwardExecutionControl(Util.java:78)\n\tat jdk.jshell/jdk.jshell.execution.Util.forwardExecutionControlAnd